      "question": "Prove that $\\frac{\\cos A - \\sin A + 1}{\\cos A + \\sin A - 1} = \\csc A + \\cot A$, using the identity $\\csc^2 A = 1 + \\cot^2 A$.",
      "answer": "$\\csc A + \\cot A$",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Divide numerator and denominator by $\\sin A$.",
          "Rewrite the expression in terms of $\\cot A$ and $\\csc A$.",
          "Replace $1$ in the numerator with $\\csc^2 A - \\cot^2 A$.",
          "Factorize the numerator using $a^2 - b^2 = (a-b)(a+b)$.",
          "Cancel the common term to simplify."
        ],
        "derivation": "\\frac{\\cot A - 1 + \\csc A}{\\cot A + 1 - \\csc A} = \\frac{\\cot A + \\csc A - (\\csc^2 A - \\cot^2 A)}{\\cot A - \\csc A + 1} = \\frac{(\\cot A + \\csc A) - (\\csc A - \\cot A)(\\csc A + \\cot A)}{\\cot A - \\csc A + 1} = \\frac{(\\cot A + \\csc A)(1 - (\\csc A - \\cot A))}{\\cot A - \\csc A + 1} = \\cot A + \\csc A"
      },
