      "question": "If $\\sin \\theta + \\cos \\theta = \\sqrt{3}$, then prove that $\\tan \\theta + \\cot \\theta = 1$.",
      "answer": "$\\tan \\theta + \\cot \\theta = 1$",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Square both sides of the given equation.",
          "Expand $(\\sin \\theta + \\cos \\theta)^2$ to get $\\sin^2 \\theta + \\cos^2 \\theta + 2 \\sin \\theta \\cos \\theta = 3$.",
          "Use identity $\\sin^2 \\theta + \\cos^2 \\theta = 1$ to find $2 \\sin \\theta \\cos \\theta = 2$, so $\\sin \\theta \\cos \\theta = 1$.",
          "Express $\\tan \\theta + \\cot \\theta$ as $\\frac{\\sin \\theta}{\\cos \\theta} + \\frac{\\cos \\theta}{\\sin \\theta}$.",
          "Simplify the fraction to $\\frac{\\sin^2 \\theta + \\cos^2 \\theta}{\\sin \\theta \\cos \\theta} = \\frac{1}{1} = 1$."
        ],
        "derivation": "(\\sin \\theta + \\cos \\theta)^2 = 3 \\implies 1 + 2 \\sin \\theta \\cos \\theta = 3 \\implies \\sin \\theta \\cos \\theta = 1; \\quad \\tan \\theta + \\cot \\theta = \\frac{\\sin^2 \\theta + \\cos^2 \\theta}{\\sin \\theta \\cos \\theta} = \\frac{1}{\\sin \\theta \\cos \\theta} = 1"
      },
